Aug 9 2005	Disappointed - very average service	My boyfriend and I stayed at Number Sixteen for a few days at the end of July. Although the hotel location was great and we had a very nice room, but the service from the front desk staff was not up to standard considering the price they charge.As we were flying over from Hong Kong overnight, we contacted the hotel in advance and asked if they could try their best to get us a room as soon as possible. Upon arrival, we were told that our room was still occupied and we waited for at least 3 hours before we could check in. The front desk gave the impression that they were not very proactive. We had to repeatedly ask the staff for updates and they did not seem to be bothered generally. The front desk also did not explain that an extra charge of 50 pounds per night would be added as part of the refundable guarantee when they took my credit card details during check-in. It was only when I went back to the front desk to inquire about the guaranteed amount as I thought they have overcharged me that they explained this extra charge. I also asked the hotel to organise taxis/car for me on two occasions as I had trains to catch. On both occasions, the car was late and one was so late that I ended up just missing my Eurostar train and had to buy another ticket to go to Paris. Again the front desk was not proactive in chasing up the driver which was not good enough.Considering the fact that Number Sixteen is not cheap, we expected much higher standard of service from the hotel and we were disappointed with the service provided by the front desk. I paid much less at Sydney House and had lovely service. Even though the hotel was lovely, I doubt I would go back to Number Sixteen again unless they make some improvement in this regard.	
Aug 1 2005	Oasis of Quiet and Luxury	The 3rd floor rafter room (superior single) was quiet, clean and beautifully decorated. The room is a little on the small size - to be expected in London, but the bed was absolute Heaven! Just steps away from South Kensington tube station (on the Picadilly Line - direct tube line to Heathrow) and easy walking distance to the Victoria &amp; Albert museum, Knightsbridge (Harrods) and Chelsea shops. Loved it! Would go back again &amp; again if the exchange rate wasn't so lousy.	
Jul 29 2005	No. 16 Pales in Comparison to Covent Garden Hotel	Call us spoiled, but we were very surprised at the difference between the room quality and service levels between No. 16 and Covent Garden Hotel. Since both are Firmdale hotels, we thought they would be comparable. We visited both hotels in July with my husband's parents. At No. 16, they gave us one room upstairs and one in the basement. My husband and I elected to choose the room in the basement (Room #1). It was small and smelled of mold. We had to keep the curtains drawn the whole time since street passers-by could easily see down into our room. And a fire exit door to the outside was located in our bathroom, which did not make us feel very safe. My in-laws' room was nicer - on the top floor - but all-in-all, the rooms at Covent Garden were much better. The service level at No. 16 had a much different feel. While at Covent Garden, each staff member truly seemed to enjoy serving their customers, while the staff at No. 16 seemed indifferent and came across as it being &quot;just a job.&quot; For example, we asked if we could move rooms, since we were not happy with Room #1 and explained why (paying full price for a substandard room). They said they were full and didn't seem a bit concerned that we were not satisfied with the room. I can only speculate that at Covent Garden, they would have at least made an attempt to remedy the situation in some fashion. There were lots of little things that were annoyances at the No. 16, such as it took an entire hour one morning to receive our cooked breakfast. In the middle of the night one night, someone was tramping up and down the hallway above our heads for about 30 minutes. I finally called the front desk to ask how much longer this would continue. At least the racket stopped soon after. In another example: they do not have movies available on site, but instead have a rental card for a nearby video store. We used their card and paid for the video at the store. The next day, we asked the front desk if we should return the video ourselves, or if they would do it. They said they would do it, and then tried to charge us for the video, which we had already paid for at the store. It seems obvious that we could not have rented the video from the store without paying for it first, but it took some time to explain this to the woman checking us out. The staff came across as not fully trained in the hotel's goings on, were not &quot;engaged&quot; with their customers, and did not get the idea that once a customer arrives, one goal is to earn his/her repeat business. For us, it underscored that even though a hotel can be nicely appointed (such as the common rooms), the service leaves a much more lasting impression. That's why Covent Garden is so successful - they understand that if customers are treated well, they will return. We recommend that if you stay at No. 16, lower your expectations a bit, and request that you not be put in one of the basement rooms.	
May 31 2005	Great central hotel!	My wife and I spent the second half of our honeymoon in London at the lovely Number Sixteen. The hotel itself has a nice boutique feel and is very centrally located in South Kensington right near the South Ken tube station. The staff was attentive, knowledgeable and helpful. They booked us theatre tickets, made us dinner reservations and scored us some tix to the sold out Chelsea Flower Show. Our room was a decent size, the bathroom was actually very large with double sinks. I believe we had the deluxe double. The style was somewhat English country, but it very much appealed to our modern tastes. The drawing room and library in the lobby were a great place to sit and chat and have an afternoon tea. The garden was beautiful and the perfect setting for a continental breakfast, which ended up being about $40 American for two people. There's plenty of restaurants and shopping nearby. Try Patara for some delicious Thai with excellent service. We would definantly stay there again and highly reccomend it to anyone looking for a cute, modern English hotel.	
Apr 20 2005	Fab little hotel!	Stayed at number sixteen just after Easter and totally loved it! The location is great, the staff were attentive, courteous and friendly and our room overlooking the garden was lovely. On arrival I noticed that the throw on the bed was not looking perhaps as white as it should have done so I phoned reception and within 5 minutes a very apologetic housekeeper arrived to replace it. The continental breakfast was good too offering a choice of fruit, yogurt, pastries, rolls, cereals and juices - there were even 4 milk options including full fat, semi-skimmed, skimmed and soy. Overall, an excellent experience - can't wait to go back!	
Mar 14 2005 	Comfortable Beds and Quaint Rooms..	Just returned from a 5 night stay at Number Sixteen with my husband. My husbnand has stayed there a few times before for business so the staff knows him well, and are very friendly. The rooms are tastefully decorated, and the beds are so comfortable. The location is really central, and a short walk to the tube station. It was too cold to enjoy the garden, but it looks like it's very well kept. I would not hesitate to recommend this hotel to anyone who enjoys a boutique hotel.	
Mar 9 2005	Comfortable and Chic in a Great Location	My husband and I stayed at Number 16 for a week over Christmas. We had spent the holidays in London before but this by far was the best hotel we had stayed in. The location is terrific - just a short walk from the Tube - the neighborhood is quiet and residential in feel with loads of good restaurants within a close walk. The rooms were comfortably sized - large by European standards with good lighting, extremely comfortable beds and lots of style. The bath was small but very luxe. Breakfast was disappointing but its never the reason we stay anywhere. Lots of better options nearby. The common rooms were living room comfortable with a honor bar stocked with some excellent wines (among other things). There seemed to be a great outdoor space that was too cold for us to enjoy this time of year. The staff was extremely pleasant and helpful even during a slow time of year for the area. I liked everything about the very comfortable, stylish place. I can't imagine a more relaxing and easy place to be in the middle of this great city. We will stay there again on our next visit.	
